6.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Tudur</i>, a derivative of British Celtic <i>Toutorīx</i>, literally ‘people’ + ‘king’. It has sometimes been taken as a Welsh equivalent of Latin <i>Theodorus</i>, from Greek <i>Theodōros</i> ‘gift of God’ (see   Theodore  ), for which the usual Welsh form is <i>Tewdwr</i>.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Tudor</i>, a variant of <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  ).","History: The Tudor royal family, English sovereigns from the accession of Henry VII in 1485 to the death of Elizabeth I in 1603, were of Welsh origin, being descended from Owain ap Maredudd ap Tudur, who held lands at Penmynydd in Anglesey."],"variants":[{"name":"Tutor","meanings":["Probably Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]},{"name":"Theodore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Tedder","meanings":["English (Surrey): from the Middle English personal name <i>Thedere</i>, <i>Teddere</i>, which is either from the Old English personal name <i>Thēodhere</i> (from <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) or from the cognate ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theudher</i>, which seems to have been adopted by the Normans. Alternatively, perhaps it may be an occupational name from Middle English <i>teddere</i> ‘one who teds’, i.e. a person whose occupation was to spread mown grass for drying.","Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]}]},{"name":"Gwenllian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>gwen</i>, the feminine form of <i>gwyn</i> ‘white, fair; blessed, holy’ (  see  Gwen  ) + <i>lliant</i> ‘flood, flow’ (probably in the transferred sense ‘foamy’ or ‘white’, referring to a pale complexion)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwenllian ferch Tudor was born about 1300 as the daughter of Tudur ap Madog and Mali ferch Ieuan. She had at least 5 sons and 3 daughters with Rhys Llwyd Ap Adam."},"et":{"about 1300–Deceased":"umbes 1300–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1300–1370":"1300–1370","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1335–1362":"1335–1362","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1363":"1363","1